# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: h8-family
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **16-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 16 bits (2 octets) wide.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Also, 16-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] 16-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 16-bit microprocessors.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] A 16-bit register can store 216 different values.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 16 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 65,535 (216 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −32,768 (−1 × 215) through 32,767 (215 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Since 216 is 65,536, a processor with 16-bit memory addresses can directly access 64 KiB (65,536 bytes) of byte-addressable memory.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] If a system uses segmentation with 16-bit segment offsets, more can be accessed.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] 1951) was quite possibly the first-ever 16-bit computer.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] It had an unusual word size for the era; most systems used six-bit character code and used a word length of some multiple of 6-bits.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] This changed with the effort to introduce ASCII, which used a 7-bit code and naturally led to the use of an 8-bit multiple which could store a single ASCII character or two binary-coded decimal digits.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] The 16-bit word length thus became more common in the 1960s, especially on minicomputer systems.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] 1965–70) include the IBM 1130, the HP 2100, the Data General Nova, and the DEC PDP-11.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Early 16-bit microprocessors, often modeled on one of the mini platforms, began to appear in the 1970s.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Early single-chip 16-bit microprocessors (c.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Other notable 16-bit processors include the Intel 8086, the Intel 80286, the WDC 65C816, and the Zilog Z8000.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] The Intel 8088 was binary compatible with the Intel 8086, and was 16-bit in that its registers were 16 bits wide, and arithmetic instructions could operate on 16-bit quantities, even though its external bus was 8 bits wide.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] 16-bit processors have been almost entirely supplanted in the personal computer industry, and are used less than 32-bit (or 8-bit) CPUs in embedded applications.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] The Motorola 68000 is sometimes called 16-bit because of the way it handles basic arithmetic.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] The instruction set was based on 32-bit numbers and the internal registers were 32 bits wide, so by common definitions, the 68000 is a 32-bit design.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Internally, 32-bit arithmetic is performed using two 16-bit operations, and this leads to some descriptions of the system as 16-bit, or "16/32".
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Such solutions have a long history in the computer field, with various designs performing math even one bit at a time, known as "serial arithmetic", while most designs by the 1970s processed at least a few bits at a time.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] A common example is the Data General Nova, which was a 16-bit design that performed 16-bit math as a series of four 4-bit operations.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] 4-bits was the word size of a widely available single-chip ALU and thus allowed for inexpensive implementation.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Using the definition being applied to the 68000, the Nova would be a 4-bit computer, or 4/16.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Not long after the introduction of the Nova, a second version was introduced, the SuperNova, which included four of the 4-bit ALUs running in parallel to perform math 16 bits at a time and therefore offer higher performance.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] This was invisible to the user and the programs, which always used 16-bit instructions and data.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] In a similar fashion, later 68000-family members, starting with the Motorola 68020, had 32-bit ALUs.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] One may also see references to systems being, or not being, 16-bit based on some other measure.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] One common one is when the address space is not the same size of bits as the internal registers.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Most 8-bit CPUs of the 1970s fall into this category; the MOS 6502, Intel 8080, Zilog Z80 and most others had 16-bit address space which provided 64 KiB of address space.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] This also meant address manipulation required two instruction cycles.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] For this reason, most processors had special 8-bit addressing modes, the zero page, improving speed.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] This sort of difference between internal register size and external address size remained in the 1980s, although often reversed, as memory costs of the era made a machine with 32-bit addressing, 2 or 4 GiB, a practical impossibility.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] For example, the 68000 exposed only 24 bits of addressing on the DIP, limiting it to a still huge (for the era) 16 MiB.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] A similar analysis applies to Intel's 80286 CPU replacement, called the 386SX, which is a 32-bit processor with 32-bit ALU and internal 32-bit data paths with a 16-bit external bus and 24-bit addressing of the processor it replaced.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] In the context of IBM PC compatible and Wintel platforms, a 16-bit application is any software written for MS-DOS, OS/2 1.x or early versions of Microsoft Windows which originally ran on the 16-bit Intel 8088 and Intel 80286 microprocessors.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Such applications used a 20-bit or 24-bit segment or selector-offset address representation to extend the range of addressable memory locations beyond what was possible using only 16-bit addresses.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Programs containing more than 216 bytes (65,536 bytes) of instructions and data therefore required special instructions to switch between their 64-kibibyte segments, increasing the complexity of programming 16-bit applications.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Single chip 16-bit microcontrollers appeared around 1983 with the introduction of the Intel 8061.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] As of 2025, 16-bit microcontrollers cost well under a US dollar in 100 quantities, similar in price to legacy 8-bit.
[src:h8-family/16-bit-computing] Even some 32-bit microcontrollers are priced under a US dollar.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] 32-bit designs have been used since the earliest days of electronic computing, in experimental systems and then in large mainframe and minicomputer systems.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The first hybrid 16/32-bit microprocessor, the Motorola 68000, was introduced in the late 1970s and used in systems such as the original Macintosh.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Fully 32-bit microprocessors such as the HP FOCUS, Motorola 68020 and Intel 80386 were launched in the early to mid 1980s and became dominant by the early 1990s.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] This generation of processors enabled the first mass-adoption of the World Wide Web.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] While 32-bit architectures are still widely used in specific applications, since the mid-2000s PCs, smartphones, and servers have moved on to 64 bits using architectures such as x86-64, with installed memory in entry-level computers often exceeding the 32-bit address limit of 4 GiB.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] A 32-bit register can store 232 different values.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 32 bits depends on the representation used.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] This means a processor with 32-bit logical or virtual addresses can directly access at most 4 GiB of byte-addressable address space.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] A processor with 32-bit physical addresses can directly access at most 4 GiB of byte-addressable main memory; 32-bit processors don't necessarily always use 32-bit physical addresses, and implementations using more or fewer exist.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] In 1948 the Manchester Baby, the first stored-program electronic computer, used a 32-bit architecture although it was only a proof of concept and had little practical capacity.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] It held only 32 32-bit words of RAM on a Williams tube, and had no addition operation, only subtraction.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Memory, other digital circuits, and wiring was expensive during the first decades of 32-bit architectures (the 1960s to the 1980s).
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Older 32-bit processor families often had many compromises and limitations to cut costs.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] This could include a 16-bit ALU, or buses narrower than 32 bits, which limited memory size or reduced the speed of operations.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] These early processors are still *32-bit*, having 32-bit registers and instructions to manipulate 32-bit quantities.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] For example, the IBM System/360 Model 30 had an 8-bit ALU, 8-bit internal data paths, and an 8-bit path to memory, and the original Motorola 68000 had a 16-bit data ALU and a 16-bit external data bus, but had 32-bit registers and a 32-bit oriented instruction set.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The 68000 design was sometimes referred to as *16/32-bit*.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] However, the opposite is often true for newer 32-bit designs.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Likewise, the PowerPC 604 is a 32-bit machine with a 64-bit external data bus.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] 32-bit instruction set architectures used for embedded computing include the 68000 family and ColdFire, x86, ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, and Infineon TriCore architectures.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] On the x86 architecture, 32-bit applications normally use the 32-bit linear address space possible with the 80386 and later chips.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The term came about because MS-DOS, Windows and OS/2 were originally written for the 8088/8086 or 80286, 16-bit microprocessors with a segmented address space where programs had to switch between segments to reach more than 64 kilobytes of memory, causing performance to suffer.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Programming with segments is complicated; requiring special keywords or *memory models* in assembly and high level languages.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The 80386 and successors support the 80286's 16-bit segments reuse the technique for 32-bit address offsets.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] If the base address of all 32-bit segments is set to 0, and segment registers are not used explicitly, the segmentation can be forgotten and the processor appears as having a simple linear 32-bit address space.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Operating systems like Windows or OS/2 provide the possibility to run 16-bit (segmented) programs as well as 32-bit programs.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] The former possibility exists for backward compatibility and the latter is usually meant to be used for new software development.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] 32-bit digital images usually refers to RGBA color space, with every pixel using eight bits each for red, green, blue and transparency.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] Other image formats such as RGBE also use 32 bits per pixel.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] In digital images, 32-bit sometimes refers to high-dynamic-range imaging (HDR) formats that use 32 bits per channel, a total of 96 bits per pixel.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] 32-bit-per-channel images are used to represent values more precisely than sRGB color space allows.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] This precision can be used to retain more detail when editing the image.
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] A 32-bit file format is a binary file format for which each elementary information is defined on 32 bits (or 4 bytes).
[src:h8-family/32-bit-computing] An example of such a format is the Enhanced Metafile Format.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] 4-bit computation is largely obsolete, i.e.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] CPUs supporting 4-bit as the maximum size, or 4-bit data bus are no longer available, but 4-bit microcontrollers, such as the EM Microelectronic EM6580, are still available as of 2026.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] 4-bit processors were widely used in electronic calculators and other roles where decimal math was used, like electronic cash registers, microwave oven timers, and so forth.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] This is because a 4-bit value holds a single binary-coded decimal (BCD) digit, making it a natural size for directly processing decimal values.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] As a 4-bit value is generally too small to hold a memory address for real-world programs or data, the address bus of these systems was generally larger.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] For instance, the canonical 4-bit microprocessor, the Intel 4004, had a 12-bit address format.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] 4-bit designs were used only for a short period when integrated circuits were still expensive, and were found primarily in cost-sensitive roles.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] While 4-bit computing is mostly obsolete, 4-bit values are still used in the same decimal-centric roles they were developed for, and modern implementations are generally much wider and process multiple 4-bit values in parallel.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] By the 1990s, most such uses had been replaced by general purpose binary designs.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] A 4-bit processor may seem limited, but it is a good match for calculators, where each decimal digit fits into four bits.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Some of the first microprocessors had a 4-bit word length and were developed around 1970.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The first commercial microprocessor was the binary-coded decimal (BCD-based) Intel 4004, developed for calculator applications in 1971; it had a 4-bit word length, but had 8-bit instructions and 12-bit addresses.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] It was succeeded by the Intel 4040, which added interrupt support and a variety of other new features.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The first commercial single-chip computer was the 4-bit Texas Instruments TMS 1000 (1974).
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] It contained a 4-bit CPU with a Harvard architecture and 8-bit-wide instructions, an on-chip instruction ROM, and an on-chip data RAM with 4-bit words.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The Rockwell PPS-4 was another early 4-bit processor, introduced in 1972, which had a long lifetime in handheld games and similar roles.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] It was steadily improved and by 1975 been combined with several support chips to make a one-chip computer.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The 4-bit processors were programmed in assembly language or Forth, e.g.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The 1970s saw the emergence of 4-bit software applications for mass markets like pocket calculators.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] During the 1980s, 4-bit microprocessors were used in handheld electronic games to keep costs low.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] In the 1970s and 1980s, a number of research and commercial computers used bit slicing, in which the CPU's arithmetic logic unit (ALU) was built from multiple 4-bit-wide sections, each section including a chip such as an Am2901 or 74181.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The Zilog Z80 (discontinued in 2024), although it is an 8-bit microprocessor, has a 4-bit ALU.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Although the Data General Nova is a series of 16-bit minicomputers, the original Nova and the Nova 1200 internally processed numbers 4 bits at a time with a 4-bit ALU, sometimes called "nybble-serial".
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The HP Saturn processors, used in many Hewlett-Packard calculators between 1984 and 2003 (including the HP 48 series of scientific calculators) are "4-bit" (or hybrid 64-/4-bit) machines.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] They string multiple 4-bit words together, e.g. to form a 20-bit memory address, and most of the registers are 64 bits wide, storing 16 4-bit digits.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Operations were performed nybble-serial.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] In addition, some early calculators – such as the 1967 Casio AL-1000, the 1972 Sinclair Executive, and the aforementioned 1984 HP Saturn – had 4-bit datapaths that accessed their registers 4 bits (one BCD digit) at a time.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] One bicycle computer specifies that it uses a "4 bit, 1-chip microcomputer".
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Other typical uses include coffee makers, infrared remote controls, and security alarms.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The processor in Barbie typewriters that can encrypt is a 4-bit microcontroller.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Western Digital used a 4-bit microcontroller as the basis for their WD2412 time-of-day clock.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The Grundy Newbrain computer uses a 4-bit microcontroller to manage its keyboard, tape I/O, and its built-in 16 character VF alphanumeric display.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] The Apple Lisa utilizes a 4-bit microcontroller to control the keyboard, mouse, RTC, and soft power switch.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] With 4 bits, it is possible to create 16 different values.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] All single-digit hexadecimal numbers can be written with four bits.
[src:h8-family/4-bit-computing] Binary-coded decimal is a digital encoding method for numbers using decimal notation, with each decimal digit represented by four bits.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **64-bit** integers, memory addresses, or other data units are those that are 64 bits wide.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Also, 64-bit central processing units (CPU) and arithmetic logic units (ALU) are those that are based on processor registers, address buses, or data buses of that size.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A computer that uses such a processor is a 64-bit computer.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] From the software perspective, 64-bit computing means the use of machine code with 64-bit virtual memory addresses.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The term *64-bit* also describes a generation of computers in which 64-bit processors are the norm.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64 bits is a word size that defines certain classes of computer architecture, buses, memory, and CPUs and, by extension, the software that runs on them.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64-bit CPUs have been used in supercomputers since the 1970s (Cray-1, 1975) and in reduced instruction set computers (RISC) based workstations and servers since the early 1990s.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In 2003, 64-bit CPUs were introduced to the mainstream PC market in the form of x86-64 processors and the PowerPC G5.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A 64-bit register can hold any of 264 (over 18 quintillion or 1.8×1019) different values.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 64 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Hence, a processor with 64-bit memory addresses can directly access 264 bytes (16 exabytes or EB) of byte-addressable memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] With no further qualification, a *64-bit computer architecture* generally has integer and addressing registers that are 64 bits wide, allowing direct support for 64-bit data types and addresses.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, a CPU might have external data buses or address buses with different sizes from the registers, even larger (the 32-bit Pentium had a 64-bit data bus, for instance).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Processor registers are typically divided into several groups: *integer*, *floating-point*, *single instruction, multiple data* (SIMD), *control*, and often special registers for address arithmetic which may have various uses and names such as *address*, *index*, or *base registers*.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, in modern designs, these functions are often performed by more general purpose *integer* registers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In most processors, only integer or address-registers can be used to address data in memory; the other types of registers cannot.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The size of these registers therefore normally limits the amount of directly addressable memory, even if there are registers, such as floating-point registers, that are wider.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most high performance 32-bit and 64-bit processors (some notable exceptions are older or embedded ARM architecture (ARM) and 32-bit MIPS architecture (MIPS) CPUs) have integrated floating point hardware, which is often, but not always, based on 64-bit units of data.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] For example, although the x86/x87 architecture has instructions able to load and store 64-bit (and 32-bit) floating-point values in memory, the internal floating-point data and register format is 80 bits wide, while the general-purpose registers are 32 bits wide.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In contrast, the 64-bit Alpha family uses a 64-bit floating-point data and register format, and 64-bit integer registers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Many computer instruction sets are designed so that a single integer register can store the memory address to any location in the computer's physical or virtual memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Therefore, the total number of addresses to memory is often determined by the width of these registers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The IBM System/360 of the 1960s was an early 32-bit computer; it had 32-bit integer registers, although it only used the low order 24 bits of a word for addresses, resulting in a 16 MiB (16 × 10242 bytes) address space.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A 32-bit address register meant that 232 addresses, or 4 GB of random-access memory (RAM), could be referenced.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] When these architectures were devised, 4 GB of memory was so far beyond the typical amounts (4 MiB) in installations, that this was considered to be enough *headroom* for addressing.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 4.29 billion addresses were considered an appropriate size to work with for another important reason: 4.29 billion integers are enough to assign unique references to most entities in applications like databases.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most modern computers contain room for 8-32 billion unique addresses inside of their random-access memory, a 64 bit architecture can access an address 2 billion times higher.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The full 64 bit space will likely never be used.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Some supercomputer architectures of the 1970s and 1980s, such as the Cray-1, used registers up to 64 bits wide, and supported 64-bit integer arithmetic, although they did not support 64-bit addressing.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In the mid-1980s, Intel i860 development began culminating in a 1989 release; the i860 had 32-bit integer registers and 32-bit addressing, so it was not a fully 64-bit processor, although its graphics unit supported 64-bit integer arithmetic.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, 32 bits remained the norm until the early 1990s, when the continual reductions in the cost of memory led to installations with amounts of RAM approaching 4 GB, and the use of virtual memory spaces exceeding the 4 GB ceiling became desirable for handling certain types of problems.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In response, MIPS and DEC developed 64-bit microprocessor architectures, initially for high-end workstation and server machines.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] By the mid-1990s, HAL Computer Systems, Sun Microsystems, IBM, Silicon Graphics, and Hewlett-Packard had developed 64-bit architectures for their workstation and server systems.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A notable exception to this trend were mainframes from IBM, which then used 32-bit data and 31-bit address sizes; the IBM mainframes did not include 64-bit processors until 2000.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] During the 1990s, several low-cost 64-bit microprocessors were used in consumer electronics and embedded applications.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Notably, the Nintendo 64 and the PlayStation 2 had 64-bit microprocessors before their introduction in personal computers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] High-end printers, network equipment, and industrial computers also used 64-bit microprocessors, such as the Quantum Effect Devices R5000.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64-bit computing started to trickle down to the personal computer desktop from 2003 onward, when some models in Apple's Macintosh lines switched to PowerPC 970 processors (termed *G5* by Apple), and Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) released its first 64-bit x86-64 processor.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Physical memory eventually caught up with 32-bit limits.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In 2023, laptop computers were commonly equipped with 16GB and servers starting from 64 GB of memory, greatly exceeding the 4 GB address capacity of 32 bits.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , which uses 64-bit data words and 32- or 64-bit instruction words.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] vector supercomputer, which uses a 64-bit word architecture (prior CDC systems were based on a 60-bit architecture).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] integers; 64-bit and 128-bit floating point; 32-bit, 64-bit, and 128-bit packed decimal and a 128-bit accumulator register.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The architecture has survived through a succession of ICL and Fujitsu machines.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The latest is the Fujitsu Supernova, which emulates the original environment on 64-bit Intel processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] supercomputer, which is based on a 64-bit word architecture and will form the basis for later Cray vector supercomputers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The Elxsi architecture has 64-bit data registers but a 32-bit address space.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Marketed as a "64-Bit Microprocessor", it had essentially a 32-bit architecture, enhanced with a 3D graphics unit capable of 64-bit integer operations.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , which includes some 64-bit wide data paths in its architecture.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A 1998 to 1999 launch date was targeted.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] IBM releases the A10 and A30 microprocessors, the first 64-bit PowerPC AS processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] IBM also releases a 64-bit AS/400 system upgrade, which can convert the operating system, database and applications.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] video game console, built around a low-cost variant of the MIPS R4000.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Intel ships its IA-64 processor line, after repeated delays in getting to market.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] and targeting high-end servers, sales fail to meet expectations.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] architecture which is the first x86-based 64-bit processor architecture.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Intel maintains that its Itanium chips would remain its only 64-bit processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Intel, reacting to the market success of AMD, admits it has been developing a clone of the AMD64 extensions named IA-32e (later renamed EM64T, then yet again renamed to Intel 64).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] processor families supporting the new 64-bit instruction set.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , servers, workstations, and other appliances.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] as the first mainstream x86-64 processor for its mobile, desktop, and workstation line.
