[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] with support for AMD64 and EM64T processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] "Tiger" which provides limited support for 64-bit command-line applications on machines with PowerPC 970 processors; later versions for Intel-based Macs supported 64-bit command-line applications on Macs with EM64T processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] x64 Edition for AMD64 and EM64T processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , including a 64-bit version for AMD64/EM64T processors that retains 32-bit compatibility.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] "Leopard", which fully supports 64-bit applications on machines with PowerPC 970 or EM64T processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , which, like Windows Vista, includes a full 64-bit version for AMD64/Intel 64 processors; most new computers are loaded by default with a 64-bit version.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , which is the first 64-bit only server operating system.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] , "Snow Leopard", which ships with a 64-bit kernel for AMD64/Intel64 processors, although only certain recent models of Apple computers will run the 64-bit kernel by default.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most applications bundled with Mac OS X 10.6 are now also 64-bit.
