[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, not all instruction sets, and not all processors implementing those instruction sets, support a full 64-bit virtual or physical address space.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The x86-64 architecture (as of March 2024) allows 48 bits for virtual memory and, for any given processor, up to 52 bits for physical memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] These limits allow memory sizes of 256 TB (256 × 10244 bytes) and 4 PB (4 × 10245 bytes), respectively.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A PC cannot currently contain 4 petabytes of memory (due to the physical size of the memory chips), but AMD envisioned large servers, shared memory clusters, and other uses of physical address space that might approach this in the foreseeable future.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Thus the 52-bit physical address provides ample room for expansion while not incurring the cost of implementing full 64-bit physical addresses.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Similarly, the 48-bit virtual address space was designed to provide 65,536 (216) times the 32-bit limit of 4 GB (4 × 10243 bytes), allowing room for later expansion and incurring no overhead of translating full 64-bit addresses.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The Power ISA v3.0 allows 64 bits for an effective address, mapped to a segmented address with between 65 and 78 bits allowed, for virtual memory, and, for any given processor, up to 60 bits for physical memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The Oracle SPARC Architecture 2015 allows 64 bits for virtual memory and, for any given processor, between 40 and 56 bits for physical memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The ARM AArch64 Virtual Memory System Architecture allows from 48 to 56 bits for virtual memory and, for any given processor, from 32 to 56 bits for physical memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The DEC Alpha specification requires minimum of 43 bits of virtual memory address space (8 TB) to be supported, and hardware need to check and trap if the remaining unsupported bits are zero (to support compatibility on future processors).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Alpha 21064 supported 43 bits of virtual memory address space (8 TB) and 34 bits of physical memory address space (16 GB).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Alpha 21164 supported 43 bits of virtual memory address space (8 TB) and 40 bits of physical memory address space (1 TB).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Alpha 21264 supported user-configurable 43 or 48 bits of virtual memory address space (8 TB or 256 TB) and 44 bits of physical memory address space (16 TB).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A change from a 32-bit to a 64-bit architecture is a fundamental alteration, as most operating systems must be extensively modified to take advantage of the new architecture, because that software has to manage the actual memory addressing hardware.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The operating systems for those 64-bit architectures generally support both 32-bit and 64-bit applications.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] One significant exception to this is the IBM AS/400, software for which is compiled into a virtual instruction set architecture (ISA) called *Technology Independent Machine Interface* (TIMI); TIMI code is then translated to native machine code by low-level software before being executed.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The translation software is all that must be rewritten to move the full OS and all software to a new platform, as when IBM transitioned the native instruction set for AS/400 from the older 32/48-bit *IMPI* to the newer 64-bit *PowerPC-AS*, codenamed *Amazon*.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The IMPI instruction set was quite different from even 32-bit PowerPC, so this transition was even bigger than moving a given instruction set from 32 to 64 bits.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] On 64-bit hardware with x86-64 architecture (AMD64), most 32-bit operating systems and applications can run with no compatibility issues.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A compiled Java program can run on a 32- or 64-bit Java virtual machine with no modification.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The lengths and precision of all the built-in types, such as `char`, `short`, `int`, `long`, `float`, and `double`, and the types that can be used as array indices, are specified by the standard and are not dependent on the underlying architecture.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Java programs that run on a 64-bit Java virtual machine have access to a larger address space.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Speed is not the only factor to consider in comparing 32-bit and 64-bit processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Applications such as multi-tasking, stress testing, and clustering – for high-performance computing (HPC) – may be more suited to a 64-bit architecture when deployed appropriately.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] For this reason, 64-bit clusters have been widely deployed in large organizations, such as IBM, HP, and Microsoft.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A common misconception is that 64-bit architectures are no better than 32-bit architectures unless the computer has more than 4 GB of random-access memory.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This code first creates 5 values: a, b, c, d and e; and then puts them in a loop.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] During the loop, this code changes the value of b to the value of a, the value of c to the value of b, the value of d to the value of c and the value of e to the value of d.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This has the same effect as changing all the values to a.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] If a processor can keep only two or three values or variables in registers, it would need to move some values between memory and registers to be able to process variables d and e also; this is a process that takes many CPU cycles.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A processor that can hold all values and variables in registers can loop through them with no need to move data between registers and memory for each iteration.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This behavior can easily be compared with virtual memory, although any effects are contingent on the compiler.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The main disadvantage of 64-bit architectures is that, relative to 32-bit architectures, the same data occupies more space in memory (due to longer pointers and possibly other types, and alignment padding).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This increases the memory requirements of a given process and can have implications for efficient processor cache use.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Maintaining a partial 32-bit model is one way to handle this, and is in general reasonably effective.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] For example, the z/OS operating system takes this approach, requiring program code to reside in 31-bit address spaces (the high order bit is not used in address calculation on the underlying hardware platform) while data objects can optionally reside in 64-bit regions.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Not all such applications require a large address space or manipulate 64-bit data items, so these applications do not benefit from these features.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] x86-based 64-bit systems sometimes lack equivalents of software that is written for 32-bit architectures.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The most severe problem in Microsoft Windows is incompatible device drivers for obsolete hardware.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most 32-bit application software can run on a 64-bit operating system in a compatibility mode, also termed an emulation mode, e.g., Microsoft WoW64 Technology for IA-64 and AMD64.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The 64-bit Windows Native Mode driver environment runs atop 64-bit NTDLL.DLL, which cannot call 32-bit Win32 subsystem code (often devices whose actual hardware function is emulated in user mode software, like Winprinters).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Because 64-bit drivers for most devices were unavailable until early 2007 (Vista x64), using a 64-bit version of Windows was considered a challenge.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, the trend has since moved toward 64-bit computing, more so as memory prices dropped and the use of more than 4 GB of RAM increased.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most manufacturers started to provide both 32-bit and 64-bit drivers for new devices, so unavailability of 64-bit drivers ceased to be a problem.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64-bit drivers were not provided for many older devices, which could consequently not be used in 64-bit systems.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Driver compatibility was less of a problem with open-source drivers, as 32-bit ones could be modified for 64-bit use.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Support for hardware made before early 2007, was problematic for open-source platforms, due to the relatively small number of users.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64-bit versions of Windows cannot run 16-bit software.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, most 32-bit applications will work well.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] 64-bit users are forced to install a virtual machine of a 16- or 32-bit operating system to run 16-bit applications or use one of the alternatives for NTVDM.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Mac OS X 10.4 "Tiger" and Mac OS X 10.5 "Leopard" had only a 32-bit kernel, but they can run 64-bit user-mode code on 64-bit processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Mac OS X 10.6 "Snow Leopard" had both 32- and 64-bit kernels, and, on most Macs, used the 32-bit kernel even on 64-bit processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This allowed those Macs to support 64-bit processes while still supporting 32-bit device drivers; although not 64-bit drivers and performance advantages that can come with them.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Mac OS X 10.7 "Lion" ran with a 64-bit kernel on more Macs, and OS X 10.8 "Mountain Lion" and later macOS releases only have a 64-bit kernel.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] On systems with 64-bit processors, both the 32- and 64-bit macOS kernels can run 32-bit user-mode code, and all versions of macOS up to macOS Mojave (10.14) include 32-bit versions of libraries that 32-bit applications would use, so 32-bit user-mode software for macOS will run on those systems.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] The 32-bit versions of libraries have been removed by Apple in macOS Catalina (10.15).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Linux and most other Unix-like operating systems, and the C and C++ toolchains for them, have supported 64-bit processors for many years.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Many applications and libraries for those platforms are open-source software, written in C and C++, so that if they are 64-bit-safe, they can be compiled into 64-bit versions.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This source-based distribution model, with an emphasis on frequent releases, makes availability of application software for those operating systems less of an issue.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In 32-bit programs, pointers and data types such as integers generally have the same length.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This is not necessarily true on 64-bit machines.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Mixing data types in programming languages such as C and its descendants such as C++ and Objective-C may thus work on 32-bit implementations but not on 64-bit implementations.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] In many programming environments for C and C-derived languages on 64-bit machines, `int` variables are still 32 bits wide, but long integers and pointers are 64 bits wide.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] These are described as having an *LP64* data model, which is an abbreviation of "Long, Pointer, 64".
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Other models are the *ILP64* data model in which all three data types are 64 bits wide, and even the *SILP64* model where *short* integers are also 64 bits wide.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, in most cases the modifications required are relatively minor and straightforward, and many well-written programs can simply be recompiled for the new environment with no changes.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Another alternative is the *LLP64* model, which maintains compatibility with 32-bit code by leaving both `int` and `long` as 32-bit.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] *LL* refers to the *long long integer* type, which is at least 64 bits on all platforms, including 32-bit environments.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] There are also systems with 64-bit processors using an *ILP32* data model, with the addition of 64-bit long long integers; this is also used on many platforms with 32-bit processors.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This model reduces code size and the size of data structures containing pointers, at the cost of a much smaller address space, a good choice for some embedded systems.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] For instruction sets such as x86 and ARM in which the 64-bit version of the instruction set has more registers than does the 32-bit version, it provides access to the additional registers without the space penalty.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] It is common in 64-bit RISC machines, explored in x86 as x32 ABI, and has recently been used in the Apple Watch Series 4 and 5.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] A programming model is a choice made to suit a given compiler, and several can coexist on the same OS.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] However, the programming model chosen as the primary model for the OS application programming interface (API) typically dominates.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Another consideration is the data model used for device drivers.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Drivers make up the majority of the operating system code in most modern operating systems (although many may not be loaded when the operating system is running).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Many drivers use pointers heavily to manipulate data, and in some cases have to load pointers of a certain size into the hardware they support for direct memory access (DMA).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This problem is solved by having the OS take the memory restrictions of the device into account when generating requests to drivers for DMA, or by using an input–output memory management unit (IOMMU).
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] Most 64-bit architectures that are derived from a 32-bit version of the same architecture can execute code written for the 32-bit version natively, with no performance penalty.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] For example, x86-64 processors can run IA-32 applications at full speed.
[src:h8-family/64-bit-computing] This kind of support is commonly called *bi-arch support* or more generally *multi-arch support*.
[src:h8-family/78k] Its application area is mainly simple mechanical system controls and man-machine interfaces.
[src:h8-family/78k] Regarding software development tools, C compilers and macro-assemblers are available.
[src:h8-family/78k] As for development tool hardware, full probing-pod type and debug port type in-circuit emulators, and flash ROM programmers are available.
[src:h8-family/78k] Historically, the family has 11 series with 9 instruction set architectures.
[src:h8-family/78k] As of 2018, 3 instruction set architectures, those are 8-bit 78K0, 8-bit 78K0S, and 16-/8-bit 78K0R, are still promoted for customers' new designs.
[src:h8-family/78k] But in most of cases, migration to RL78 Family, which is a successor of 78K0R and almost binary level compatible with 78K0R, is recommended.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K0 Series (also known as 78K/0) is a long-running 8-bit single chip microcontroller, which is the basis of 78K0S and 78K0R Series.
[src:h8-family/78k] It contains 8× 8-bit registers ×4 banks.
[src:h8-family/78k] For 16-bit calculating instructions, it performs ALU operation twice.
[src:h8-family/78k] Each instructions are performed serially without instruction pipelining.
[src:h8-family/78k] Some variants of 78K0 have affordable and compact type 8-bit R-2R D/A converter, which does not have monotonicity because it is not trimmed for adjustment nor followed by operational amplifier.
[src:h8-family/78k] In its earlier stage, the *Program Memory* was one-time PROM (OTP), UV-EPROM, or mask ROM.
[src:h8-family/78k] But with the times, it became flash memory.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K0S Series (also known as 78K/0S) is a low-end version of 78K0.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 8× 8-bit registers, but without any banks.
[src:h8-family/78k] In addition, some instructions, such as multiplication and division, are removed from 78K0 instruction set architecture.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K0R Series is a 16-bit single-chip microcontroller with 3-stage instruction pipelining.
[src:h8-family/78k] Its instruction set is similar to 78K0 and covers 16- and 8-bit operations.
[src:h8-family/78k] 75 instructions out of 80 are identical with that of RL78 Family; its successor.
[src:h8-family/78k] 178K0 Series (also known as 178K/0) is a successor of NEC's 17K Family 4-bit microcontroller for *DTS (Digital Tuning Systems)* and *remote controls*.
[src:h8-family/78k] It integrates 17K family's peripheral functions with the 78K0 8-bit CPU core on a chip.
[src:h8-family/78k] 178K0S Series (also known as 178K/0S) is also a successor of 17K Family with the 78K0S CPU core.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K4 Series (also known as 78K/4) is a 16-bit single-chip microcontroller with 16 and 8-bit operations.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 16× 8-bit registers ×4 banks, which can be also used for 8× 16-bit registers ×4 banks.
[src:h8-family/78k] Some of these registers can be also used as 24-bit extension for addressing modes.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has microcode-based operations named *Macro Service* with interrupt functions.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K7 Series (also known as 78K/7) is a 32-bit single-chip microcontroller with 32, 16 and 8 bit operations.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 8× 32-bit registers ×16 banks, which can be also used for 16× 16-bit registers ×16 banks and 16× 8-bit registers ×16 banks.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 24-bit 16M Byte linear address space.
[src:h8-family/78k] It is used for some Quantum *Fireball* products, but shortly replaced with *V850* Family 32-bit RISC microcontrollers.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K6 Series (also known as 78K/6) is a 16-bit single-chip microcontroller.
[src:h8-family/78k] Its life-time was short, and less variants.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K1 Series (also known as 78K/1) is an 8-bit single-chip microcontroller.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K1 series is targeted for servo controls of videocassette recorders. μPD78148 sub-series integrates 2 operational amplifiers.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K3 Series (also known as 78K/3) is a 16-bit single-chip microcontroller with 16 and 8 bit operations.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 16× 8-bit ×8 banks, which can be also used for 8× 16-bit registers ×8 banks.
[src:h8-family/78k] It is developed as high-end series of 78K Family.
[src:h8-family/78k] This series is used for hard disk drives, especially Quantum *Fireball* Series. μPD78364 sub-series is used for inverter compressor controls.
[src:h8-family/78k] It is also used for traction control systems of some cars.
[src:h8-family/78k] 78K2 Series (also known as 78K/2) is an 8-bit single-chip microcontroller.
[src:h8-family/78k] It is developed as general purpose series of 78K Family.
[src:h8-family/78k] 87AD Family is an 8-bit single-chip microcontroller.
[src:h8-family/78k] Its instruction set architecture became the basis of 78K.
[src:h8-family/78k] 17K Family is a 4-bit single-chip microcontroller, especially dedicated for *DTS (Digital Tuning Systems)* and *remote controls*.
[src:h8-family/78k] It has 2 plane of 128× 4-bit register files, and sophisticated fully orthogonal instruction set.
[src:h8-family/78k] This instruction set is completely different from that of 78K Family.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The **Hitachi H8** is a large family of 8-bit, 16-bit and 32-bit microcontrollers made by Renesas Technology, originating in the early 1990s within Hitachi Semiconductor.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The original design, the **H8/300**, was an 8-bit processor that had 16-bit registers and ALU which allowed some 16-bit operations.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Two upgraded versions were introduced, the **H8/300L** that expanded the instructions to become a full 16-bit machine while being optimized for low cost, and the **H8/300H** which further expanded the registers to allow 32-bit operations and was optimized for low-power/high-performance roles.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The entire line was sold to Renesas in 2003.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Renesas continues to sell the designs as of 2023, but only to existing customers.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] An administrator on the Renesas user community boards commented in 2011 that there are no plans for further development of H8 based products.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] H8 was supported in the Linux kernel starting with version 4.2 but support was removed in version 5.19.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] For higher performance needs, Hitachi introduced its SuperH family of 32-bit RISC-like microcontrollers, which have largely replaced the H8.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Subfamilies include the 8/16-bit H8/300 and H8/500, the 16/32-bit H8/300H and H8S and the 32-bit H8SX series, each with dozens of different variants, varying by speed, selection of built-in peripherals such as timers, interrupts and serial ports, and amounts of ROM, flash memory and RAM.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Built-in ROM and flash memory tends to range from 16 KB to 1024 KB, and RAM from 512 B to 512 KB.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The basic architecture of the H8 is patterned after the DEC PDP-11 architecture, with eight 16-bit registers (the H8/300H and H8S have an additional bank of eight 16-bit registers), and a variety of addressing modes.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Unlike the PDP-11 however, the H8 architecture employs big-endian byte ordering.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Both H8/300H and H8S have eight 32-bit registers, each of which can be treated as one 32-bit register, two 16-bit registers, or two 8-bit registers, with the H8S having an internal 32-bit configuration.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] Several companies provide compilers for the H8 family, and there is a complete GCC port, including a simulator.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] There are also various hardware emulators available.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The family is continued with the H8SX 32-bit controllers.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] H8S may be found in digital cameras, the Cybiko handheld computers, some ThinkPad notebooks, printer controllers, smart cards, chess computers, music synthesizers such as the Yamaha FS1R, Roland SC-55 and Roland JV880 and in various automotive subsystems.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] The LEGO Mindstorms RCX, an advanced robot toy/educational tool, uses the H8/300.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] An H8/3002 was used as a sound processor by Namco for various games it made in the late 1990s, notably those using its System 12 architecture and by Yamaha for the DB50XG and DB60XG daughterboards and the SW60XG ISA bus sound card.
[src:h8-family/h8-family] H8/500 was being also used on a Nokia 2110 phone.
